./dissolve-workspace/iteration-1/artifacts/solo-claude.html:139:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ <b>category membership</b></span></td><td><b>Irreplaceable.</b> "Does alcoholism belong in the set we <em>call</em> diseases?" I cannot rewrite this without the word, because "disease" has no crisp definition the members share — it is a family-resemblance cluster. This is where the substitution jams: <em>the confusion is located here.</em> The word's whole power is doing all six jobs at once and implying they must co-vary.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/iteration-1/artifacts/solo-claude.html:164:  Q --> SQ2["SQ2: impaired control? — drinks despite trying to stop"]
./dissolve-workspace/iteration-1/artifacts/solo-claude.html:194:        <td><b>SQ2</b> Is control impaired?</td>
./dissolve-workspace/iteration-1/artifacts/solo-claude.html:233:    <p class="verdict">"Is alcoholism a disease?" is not one factual question but a bundle wearing one word. Its <em>empirical</em> parts have answers — the body <em>is</em> altered (SQ1: yes), control <em>is</em> impaired to a degree (SQ2: yes, on a continuum), and it is <em>not</em> a discrete natural kind but a multifactorial spectrum (SQ3: no). Its <em>value</em> parts — blame (SQ5) and the right social response (SQ4) — are genuine questions but not factual ones; no observation decides them. And the bare label question itself is <b>empty</b>: "disease" is a family-resemblance cluster with no membership test, so once the sub-answers are in, appending "…therefore a disease, yes/no" licenses no new anticipation. The real dispute people are having under this word is SQ5 — <em>is the drinker to blame?</em> — routed through "disease" because our culture pre-wires that label to "not your fault."</p>
./dissolve-workspace/iteration-1/artifacts/solo-claude.html:239:      <li><b>SQ5 (value):</b> the responsibility question survives intact. Impaired control (SQ2) is a matter of degree, so blame is too — this is where the honest disagreement lives, and it should be argued as ethics, not smuggled through a medical label.</li>
