./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:122:    <p>Two internal handles collide. One handle says: drinking is an action performed by a person; actions invite responsibility, incentives, trust, blame, apology, and repair. The other says: repeated drinking can keep happening after sincere vows, losses, shame, withdrawal, craving, and visible harm; that looks less like ordinary preference and more like a process that has partly escaped simple command. The word <em>disease</em> is asked to settle that collision by category membership. The territory contains patterns, mechanisms, choices, harms, and interventions. The map-confusion is asking one word to distribute all the moral and practical consequences.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:133:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">alcoholism</span></span></td><td>A recurring pattern in which a person drinks in ways that bring predictable harm, violate later or prior intentions, and disrupt health, relationships, work, safety, or self-respect. If this pattern is absent, the original question has no target.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:134:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span>, <span class="from">illness</span>, <span class="from">disorder</span>, <span class="from">pathology</span>, <span class="from">medical condition</span></span></td><td>A packed cluster: bodily or learned mechanisms, impaired control, need for treatment, eligibility for care, reduced contempt, possible accommodation, and a different style of accountability.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:135:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">real</span>, <span class="from">really</span>, <span class="from">true</span>, <span class="from">actually</span>, <span class="from">is</span></span></td><td>A request for privileged category membership after the observable facts are already fixed. Replace it with: what would we expect to observe, and what response would change?</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:136:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">just</span>, <span class="from">merely</span>, <span class="from">only</span></span></td><td>An attempt to collapse a multi-cause pattern into one small description, usually either "bad choice" or "body problem," while discarding the rest.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:137:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">choice</span>, <span class="from">voluntary</span></span></td><td>Actions that can respond to reasons, incentives, planning, threat, promise, habit, environment, and available help. This comes in degrees and contexts, not one switch.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:138:      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">responsible</span>, <span class="from">blameworthy</span>, <span class="from">moral failing</span></span></td><td>Questions about which responses help: trust or distrust, help or refusal, treatment or punishment, compassion or anger, repair demands or exclusion.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:153:      <li>One classifier fires: drinking is an intentional act. Intentional acts invite criticism, incentives, promises, consequences, apology, and repair.</li>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:168:      <li><strong>Policy/value:</strong> Which stance toward the person produces better outcomes: compassion, treatment, boundaries, sanctions, repair demands, or some mix?</li>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:196:      <tr><td>Target pattern: recurring harmful drinking?</td><td>Repeated episodes, predictable losses or risks, failed cutbacks, concealment, repair attempts, and a history that lets others forecast harm.</td><td>Occasional or disliked drinking without a stable harmful pattern; no reliable forecast of repeated damage from the drinking itself.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:202:      <tr><td>Policy/value: use compassion, help, boundaries, and repair rather than contempt?</td><td>If this stance is chosen and its empirical assumptions hold, I would expect earlier disclosure, less pointless humiliation, more treatment uptake, clearer boundaries, and more targeted repair.</td><td>If a contempt-first stance is chosen, I would expect deterrence only where shame and threat work; otherwise hiding, escalation, brittle trust, and less useful help.</td><td>value</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:212:    <p class="verdict">With the loaded label removed, the original question becomes a bundle of sharper questions about recurring harmful drinking, impaired control, sustaining mechanisms, intervention results, remaining agency, and response policy. The remaining bare question, "but does it belong to the special category?", is empty once those observations are fixed.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:213:    <p>For the surviving decision question, settle by consequences. A useful stance treats the pattern as harmful and partly self-propelling while preserving practical accountability: reduce triggers, offer effective help, keep boundaries, require repair where repair helps, and use blame only where blame improves prediction, prevention, or restitution. "What is deserved in the hidden essence sense?" adds no testable handle; "what response helps?" does the work.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/codex/dissolution.html:219:      <li>Policy still contains tradeoffs among compassion, safety, autonomy, trust, cost, and repair; those are decisions to make openly.</li>
