./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:135:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ involuntariness</span></td><td>Can the person stop at will, like flipping a switch, or is their control impaired / graded? <em>Rewrites cleanly.</em></td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:136:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ natural course + treatability</span></td><td>Does it follow a characteristic trajectory and respond to medical/therapeutic intervention? <em>Rewrites cleanly.</em></td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:137:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ exemption from blame</span></td><td>Should the drinker <em>not</em> be held at fault for the drinking and its harms? Here the rewrite stops being about the drinker and becomes a stance <em>we</em> take. <strong>The word will not reduce to a fact.</strong></td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:138:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ warrant for the sick role</span></td><td>Should society respond with care, coverage, and treatment rather than censure and punishment? A decision, not a description. <strong>Irreplaceable without importing an ought.</strong></td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:139:      <tr><td class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span> <span class="to">→ a natural kind ("really one")</span></td><td>Is there a fact of the matter — a joint in nature — that files this condition into the illness bin independent of our purposes? When I try to rewrite this into pure observation, <strong>nothing is left to observe</strong>; the word points at a filing decision, not a thing.</td></tr>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:164:  Q --> CTRL["SQ2: control impaired, or free to stop at will?"]
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:193:        <td><strong>SQ2</strong> Control impaired vs. free to stop at will?</td>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:196:        <td><b>empirical</b> — differ; observation shows control is <em>impaired but graded</em>, not a clean switch. This gradedness is exactly why the binary jams.</td>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:231:    <p class="verdict">"Is alcoholism a disease?" is not one question but a bundle. Tabooed and split, it becomes three empirical questions — biological changes (yes), voluntary control (impaired but graded), course and treatability (yes) — plus one genuine value/policy decision (blame and the sick role, to be settled by which response reduces harm), all wrapped in a pseudo-factual "which natural kind did the universe file it under?" that is simply <em>empty</em>. There is no further fact "is it <em>really</em> a disease" hovering above the sub-answers, because "disease" is not a joint in nature — it is a classifying decision we make for a purpose.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:232:    <p>Why the mind felt a hanging question: "disease" is the label on an <em>illness</em> folder that bundles biology + involuntariness + blamelessness + medical treatment into a single bit, sitting opposite a <em>vice</em> folder that bundles the opposites. Alcoholism splits the bundle — high on biology and impaired control, but retaining a residue of choice and incentive-responsiveness — so the one folder-bit will not latch. The stuck switch <em>is</em> the itch. Once the axes are pulled apart, each has its own clean answer and the switch dissolves.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:234:    Honest report: the itch <em>specific to the word "disease"</em> is gone — no strand is still fused under it, and I can see exactly why a mind generates the question and feels it as urgent. But a faint pull remains one layer down. SQ4's blame axis rests on "could the drinker have done otherwise?", and my empirical answer to SQ2 ("impaired but graded") does not draw the bright line that the moral intuition wants. That pull is <em>not</em> about "disease" — it is the free-will / could-have-done-otherwise question, correctly relocated beneath SQ4 rather than smuggled through the word "disease". So I judge <b>this</b> question dissolved, with that deeper question named and parked, not resolved. Calling the whole free-will problem solved here would be dishonest; leaving "disease" fused would also be dishonest. It is unbundled: the disease-confusion discharges cleanly, handing its remaining charge to a different, named question.</p>
./dissolve-workspace/runs/solo/claude/dissolution.html:239:      <li><strong>Where to set the graded-control threshold.</strong> Since SQ2 is a continuum, any place we draw "impaired enough to excuse" is itself a decision, inheriting the SQ5 and free-will threads.</li>
